Anonymous Tue 29 Mar 2022 05:07:58 No.46519283 Report
Quoted By: >>46519872
>>46518754
I write because I love to. It's not always so easy, but they days when it just falls out of you onto the keyboard are bliss. Watching your ideas shape themselves in front of you is a fascinating process that I find highly satisfying. It's just fulfilling to go from "okay, then she brings him to this room, and people react this way" to 4 or 5 lines describing the kinetics and emotion of the scene. Holding you tightly or just expecting you to follow? Do you walk casually, with short, nervous steps? Or do you stride alongside them? I want you to feel characters straining at their moral compass, unsure of what they will do next, and be disappointed in them when they don't do what they know they should.

It's not that I don't like drawing, but I find the feeling of having to leave something in a state that doesn't satisfy me very frustrating. I almost never want to look at my old drawings. I find it difficult to see past the negative space where it isn't what I wanted it to be, and look at it for what it is. I'm still practising though, and I made good progress in breaking my reliance on short-stroke sketchy lines in the aggie earlier.

I suggested this to someone the other night
Since I usually lay down the dialogue first, my usual is to leave spaces where I can paint in the how later. Other times, I can let the dialogue carry it. I don't need to tell readers every detail that happens if the pacing feels like a heated argument; sometimes none is needed.
Once a writer gets some confidence in controlling that mental camera, scenes get richer in fewer words. I love when I can just say there was a glance or someone turned away. It makes the slower-paced scenes that much more comfy, knowing they're fleeting.
